The Taxation of the Poor
Howard Chernick Andrew Reschovsky
ABSTRACT
This paper uses microsimulation modeling to estimate the annual burden offederal, state, and local taxes on the poor in two states. We find that in 1988 the average burden of taxation on poorfamilies and individuals was 15.3 percent in Massachusetts and 18 percent in New York. As most of the burden is due to state and local taxes, federal tax reform had only a minor impact on the overall tax burdens faced by the poor. Though the analysis is for two state, we argue that the basic results are applicable for most other states. Given the high incidence of persistent poverty among those who are poor in any given year, we argue that annual burdens provide a good indication of long-run burdenfor a significant proportion of the poor.
I. Introduction
