In both Massachusetts and New York the largest source of the tax burden on the poor comes from the property tax. Among those facing a property tax burden, the average tax liability is $668 in Massachusetts and $716 in New York, and the average burdens are 9.5 and 11.4 percent, respectively. Burdens on owners substantially exceed those on renters in Massachusetts, but are about equal in New York. Over 60 percent of poor families paying property taxes are tenants. In Massachusetts they face an average property tax burden of 7.9 percent of income, while poor homeowners face burdens that average 12.1 percent.
The inclusion of imputed rent in total income has a substantial impact on the property tax burdens of low-income homeowners. Imputed rent comprises about 40 percent of total income for poor owners, and in both states the average property tax burden for this group would rise by 65 percent or more if imputed rent were excluded from the income measure. For the near-poor owner, the average burden would rise by about 50 percent-from 7.8 to 12.1 percent in Massachusetts, and 7.1 to 10.6 percent in New York. Because imputed rent comprises almost half of total income for poor elderly homeowners, if it is not included in income their measured property tax burden would nearly double.
Although an appropriate measure of "ability to pay" should include imputed rents from homeownership, it should be emphasized that property taxation can create substantial economic hardship for elderly homeowners who, despite large amounts of home equity, have few liquid resources with which to pay their property taxes and provide for the other necessities of life. Although reverse-equity mortgages and tax deferral programs operated in some states may potentially increase the liquidity of home equity, most homeowners appear to be either unable or unwilling to participate in these programs.
Property tax burdens faced by poor tenants are high enough to cause economic hardship for many poor tenants. The data in Tables 1 and 2 are based on the assumption that tenants bear 75 percent of the total property tax burden on their housing unit. Although this assumption is based on a careful assessment of the low-income rental housing market, it is possible that landlords are able to shift forward to tenants either a smaller or larger share of the total burden on rental property. We thus conducted a sensitivity analysis of the forward shifting assumption by considering both 50 percent and 100 percent shifting of the tax burden. The possibility of complete forward shifting to tenants is most likely in areas, especially
