major sources of these high tax burdens are state and local sales and property taxes, and federal and state excise taxes. Because relatively few poor families paid federal income taxes even before tax reform, the Federal Tax Reform Act of 1986 was largely ineffective in reducing the total tax burden faced by the poor.
Because of the important contribution of taxes on consumption to the overall tax burden of the poor, we have paid special attention to the potential upward bias in tax burdens caused by the use of annual rather than permanent income. When we weight the estimated burden of consumption taxes according to the likelihood of persistent poverty, we find that in New York the median tax burden for the persistently poor is estimated to be 10.6 percent, as compared to 15.3 percent for the entire sample. Moreover, since most of those experiencing even temporary spells of poverty do not rise very far above the poverty line over longer time periods, the high estimated consumption tax burdens (over 25 percent of income) for the nonpersistently poor in our sample should not be completely discounted. Therefore, we argue that for the majority of poor families, high tax burdens are not simply artifacts of the annual accounting period, but indicate significant real welfare burdens.
A question that arises in the interpretation of any empirical incidence study is the sensitivity of the results to the incidence assumptions and the data employed. Because there is no consensus on property tax incidence assumptions, we have simulated the impact of several alternative assumptions. First, in line with the "new view" of property tax incidence, we have assumed that 40 percent of the burden is equivalent to a national property tax and is allocated to the owners of capital. The result of this assumption is to reduce the average property tax burden on the poor by about 30 percent, and the overall tax burden on the poor by about 15 percent. For reasons outlined earlier, the allocation of most of the property tax burden to the consumers of housing is our preferred incidence assumption for low-income families. Second, we have considered alternative forward-shifting assumptions for the property tax on rental housing. Assumptions of 50 and 100 percent shifting yielded a range of property tax burden estimates for renters from 5 to 10 percent in Massachusetts and 8 to 15 percent in New York. However, recent data on rent burdens for low-income households suggest that the upper-bound estimates may be more accurate than the lower-bound.
Although this study is based on data from only two states, we believe that the basic results hold for residents of most states. Massachusetts and New York are different from the average state in several ways, but the impact of these differences on tax burdens faced by the poor tend to be offsetting. In both states the proportion of the poor with earnings is
